NAME AND ACCREDITATION Lindenwood University was founded in 1832 and was established as Lindenwood Female College in 1853 and became a four-year university awarding baccalaureate degrees in 1918. In 1969. a separate but coordinated college. Lindenwood University for Men (also called Lindenwood II) was established. and the institution’s name was changed to the Lindenwood Colleges. The Lindenwood Evening College (Lindenwood II) was added in 1972 and the Lindenwood College for Individualized Education (Lindenwood IV or LCIE) in 1975. In 1984 the name of the institution was restored to Lindenwood College. In 1997, the school began doing business under the name of Lindenwood University, Lindenwood is accredited by the Higher Learning Commission of the North Central Association of Colleges and Schools and the Missouri Department of Elementary and Secondary Education and is a member of the Teacher Education Accreditation Council. Lindenwood University 1s authorized to grant associate's. bachelor’s, master’s, education specialist and doctoral degrees.

Effective fall 2017, an undergraduate student may repeat any course in which they earn a grade of C or lower. Only the highest grade earned will be used in the calculation of the grade point average. The letter R designates that a course is repeated or will be repeated.

Effective fall 2020. a graduate student may repeat any course in which they earn a grade of C or lower. Only the highest grade earned will be used in the calculation of the grade point average. Prior to 2020, the calculation of the GPA was an average. The letter R designates that a course is repeated or will be repeated.

ACADEMIC RENEWAL — Allows returning students to remove previous course work from calculation of their GPA after an extended absence. A returning student seeking to resume a program of study or begin a new program of study after a prolonged absence is eligible for Academic Renewal under certain conditions, please see the catalog for the criteria, No course from a term selected to be removed from GPA calculation can be used to satisfy an academic requirement (c.g., toward graduation. prerequisites, or certifications). All courses from terms will be removed from calculation of the student's GPA regardless of the grades earned. However. these courses will not be entirely crased. All courses taken by the student will still appear on their transcript. A note will appear on the student’s transcript for each redacted term.

GRADUATION Honors Undergraduate students whose cumulative grade point average is 3.94 or above receive the degree summa cum laude: 3.86 to 3.93 graduate magna cum laude: 3.70 to 3.85 graduate cum Jaude. Students completing the Honors Program are acknowledged as graduating with university honors. Courses taken for honors credit are indicated with “honors” in the course tie or with a grade of AH or BH. To be eligible for general honors, an undergraduate student must have completed a minimum of SO credit hours—in residence at Lindenwood University—and acquire the appropriate cumulative grade point average.
